1 AN ACT
2 RELATING TO SPECIAL DISTRICTS; REQUIRING A SOIL AND WATER
3 CONSERVATION DISTRICT TO LEVY TAXES UPON REQUEST OF A
4 WATERSHED DISTRICT WITHIN THE SOIL AND WATER CONSERVATION
5 DISTRICT'S BOUNDARIES; CLARIFYING DEFINITIONS; CLARIFYING THE
6 PROCEDURE FOR APPOINTING DIRECTORS OF A WATERSHED DISTRICT'S
7 BOARD OF DIRECTORS.
8
9 BE IT ENACTED BY THE LEGISLATURE OF THE STATE OF NEW MEXICO:
10 SECTION 1. Section 73-20-2 NMSA 1978 (being Laws 1957,
11 Chapter 210, Section 2, as amended) is amended to read:
12 "73-20-2. DEFINITIONS.--As used in the Watershed
13 District Act:
14 A. "directors" or "board of directors" means the
15 directors of a watershed district; and
16 B. "supervisors" or "board of supervisors" means
17 the supervisors of a soil and water conservation district in
18 which the watershed district is located."
19 SECTION 2. Section 73-20-12 NMSA 1978 (being Laws 1957,
20 Chapter 210, Section 12, as amended) is amended to read:
"73-20-12. DIRECTORS--APPOINTMENT.--
21
A. A watershed district shall be governed by a
22
board of directors appointed by the board of supervisors for
23
the soil and water conservation district in which the
24
watershed district is located. Except as provided in
25 HB 108/a
Page 1

1 Subsection C of this section, a board of directors shall
2 consist of five directors.
3 B. When appointing the initial directors for a
4 watershed district, the board of supervisors shall appoint
5 two members to serve terms of two years and three members to
6 serve terms of four years. Thereafter, new members appointed
7 to the watershed district board shall be for terms of four
8 years. Vacancies occurring before the expiration of a term
9 shall be filled by appointment for the unexpired remainder of
10 a term.
11 C. If the territory embraced within a watershed
12 district lies within more than one soil and water
13 conservation district, each soil and water conservation
14 district having a minority of the land in the watershed
15 district shall be entitled to appoint three additional
16 directors. When appointing the additional directors, the
17 board of supervisors shall appoint one director to serve a
term of two years and two directors to serve terms of four
18
years. Thereafter, each director shall be appointed for a
19
term of four years. Vacancies shall be filled by appointment
20
by the original appointing entity for the remainder of an
21
unexpired term.
22
D. The board of directors shall annually elect
23
from its membership a chair, secretary and treasurer. The
24
treasurer shall execute an official bond for the faithful
25 HB 108/a
Page 2

1 performance of the duties of office to be approved by the
2 board of directors. The bond shall be executed with at least
3 three solvent personal sureties whose solvency shall exceed
4 the amount of the bond, or by a surety company authorized to
5 do business in this state, and shall be in an amount
6 determined by the board of directors. If the treasurer is
7 required to execute a surety company bond, the premium of the
8 bond shall be paid by the board of directors.
9 E. The board of directors shall prepare and submit
10 to the department of finance and administration such reports
11 as it may require from among those required to be submitted
12 by other political subdivisions."
13 SECTION 3. Section 73-20-13 NMSA 1978 (being Laws 1957,
14 Chapter 210, Section 13, as amended) is amended to read:
15 "73-20-13. AUTHORITY.--Subject to the approval of the
16 board of supervisors, the board of directors of a watershed
17 district shall have power to:
18 A. request the board of supervisors to levy an
19 annual assessment on the real property within the watershed
district, subject to the requirements provided in Subsection
20
A of Section 73-20-17 NMSA 1978, for administration,
21
construction, operation and maintenance of works of
22
improvement within and without the district as are required
23
by the district in the performance of its functions;
24
B. acquire by purchase, gift, grant, bequest,
25 HB 108/a
Page 3

1 devise or through condemnation proceedings in the manner
2 provided in the Eminent Domain Code property or rights of way
3 necessary for the exercise of any authorized function of the
4 district; provided that no property or water rights shall be
5 condemned for the purposes of recreation;
6 C. construct, improve, operate, contract for and
7 maintain such structures as may be necessary for the
8 performance of any function authorized by the Watershed
9 District Act;
10 D. borrow money necessary for the purpose of
11 acquiring rights of way and establishing, constructing,
12 reconstructing, repairing, enlarging and maintaining the
13 structures and improvements required by the district in the
14 performance of its functions and repay these loans with the
15 proceeds of the annual assessment provided for in Subsection
16 A of this section or by the issuance, negotiation and sale of
17 its bonds as provided in Section 73-20-14 NMSA 1978; and
E. receive and grant assistance and cooperate with
18
counties, municipalities and state and federal agencies in
19
carrying out the provisions of the Watershed District Act."
20
SECTION 4. Section 73-20-15 NMSA 1978 (being Laws 1961,
21
Chapter 233, Section 3, as amended) is amended to read:
22
"73-20-15. LOANS--REPAYMENTS.--
23
A. In addition to the borrowing of money by the
24
issuance of bonds for the purposes set out in Section
25 HB 108/a
Page 4

1 73-20-13 NMSA 1978, the district may borrow money from the
2 United States department of agriculture or any other federal
3 agency if the loan can be repaid according to its terms by
4 use of the levy authorized by Subsection A of Section
5 73-20-17 NMSA 1978 and the board of supervisors has so
6 determined.
7 B. The district may also borrow money from the
8 United States department of agriculture or any other federal
9 agency if the loan can be repaid according to its terms by
10 use of the levy authorized by Subsection B of Section
11 73-20-17 NMSA 1978."
12 SECTION 5. Section 73-20-17 NMSA 1978 (being Laws 1957,
13 Chapter 210, Section 16, as amended) is amended to read:
14 "73-20-17. BUDGETS--TAX LEVY--LIMITATION.--
15 A. Within the first quarter of each calendar year,
16 the board of directors shall prepare an itemized budget of
17 the funds needed for administration, construction, operation
18 and maintenance of works of improvement and submit the budget
19 to the board of supervisors for approval. After approval of
the budget, the board of supervisors shall, by order or
20
resolution, levy an assessment sufficient to meet the budget,
21
not to exceed five dollars ($5.00), or any lower maximum
22
amount required by operation of the rate limitation
23
provisions of Section 7-37-7.1 NMSA 1978 upon the assessment
24
authorized by this section, on each one thousand dollars
25 HB 108/a
Page 5

1 ($1,000) of net taxable value, as that term is defined in the
2 Property Tax Code, of all real property subject to taxation
3 within the district, except that the limit on assessments
4 does not apply to any levy necessary to provide a sinking
5 fund for retirement of bonds authorized by Section 73-20-13
6 NMSA 1978. If a watershed district lies within more than one
7 soil and water conservation district, the board of
8 supervisors in each soil and water conservation district
9 shall approve of the budget submitted by the watershed
10 district before an assessment may be levied pursuant to this
11 subsection. A copy of the budget and order or resolution
12 shall be certified to the county assessor of the county or
13 counties involved and to the department of finance and
14 administration by July 15 of each year.
15 B. Upon receipt of a resolution adopted and
16 submitted by the board of directors, the board of supervisors
17 shall levy an assessment not to exceed five dollars ($5.00)
on each one thousand dollars ($1,000) of net taxable value,
18
as that term is defined in the Property Tax Code, of property
19
subject to taxation by the board of supervisors, in addition
20
to the levy authorized by Subsection A of this section, to
21
repay the loan if the board of supervisors approves of the
22
levy and:
23
(1) a referendum on the acceptance of the
24
loan for specified purposes is held by the board of
25 HB 108/a
Page 6

1 supervisors;
2 (2) two-thirds of the landowners vote in
3 favor of the proposal; and
4 (3) the procedures of the Local Election Act
5 or the Special Election Act as well as local government
6 ballot question election provisions in the Election Code are
7 followed as to notice, qualifications of voters and manner of
8 holding a tax authorization election are followed in the
